author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The US has intercepted a third vessel off Venezuela in less than a week, intensifying pressure on President Nicolas Maduro.
The US Coast Guard is pursuing the Bella 1, described as part of a sanctioned shadow fleet used to evade oil restrictions.
US officials say the vessel was flying a false flag, is empty, and was heading to load Venezuelan oil under a judicial seizure order.
The latest move follows the boarding of the Centuries, carrying 1.8 million barrels of sanctioned crude, and Trump’s oil blockade.
Caracas has condemned the actions as piracy and theft, vowing to raise the issue at the UN Security Council.
Washington says the measures target oil revenues funding narco-terrorism, while critics warn of legal and military escalation.
The crisis has deepened regional divisions, with Latin American leaders split over US intervention and its wider impact.

Al Jazeera’s Heidi Zhou-Castro joins us live from Washington, DC, while Teresa Bo covers regional reactions from Buenos Aires.

S
title: US intercepts third vessel off Venezuela as pressure mounts on Maduro

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Australia has marked a National Day of Reflection to honour the 15 victims of the terrorist shooting at Sydney's Bondi Beach last week. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has launched a major review of the country's law enforcement and intelligence agencies, which must report its findings by the end of April.
The review, led by a former spy chief, will examine the "right powers, structures, processes and sharing arrangements" to keep Australians safe. The investigation follows questions about the intelligence assessment of one suspect in 2019. Prime Minister Albanese has also condemned divisive anti-immigration rallies, stating they have no place in Australia in the wake of an antisemitic attack.

Al Jazeera’s Victoria Gatenby reports.

After years of support from the United States for the Ukraine war to continue “as long as it takes”, the Trump administration is now pushing to end Europe’s war – quickly and imperfectly.

To understand the implications for Europe, the US and their relations, host Steve Clemons speaks with Kurt Volker, Trump’s former special representative for Ukraine negotiations, and retired Colonel Heino Klinck, former director of US Army international affairs.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
At least nine people have been killed and 10 wounded when armed men opened fire at a tavern in a township near the city of Johannesburg in South Africa, police say, adding that some victims were “randomly shot in the streets”.
In a statement on Sunday, the police said a manhunt by Gauteng Serious and Violent Crime Investigations in collaboration with the Crime Detection Tracing Unit is under way for those involved in the shooting, which took place in the Bekkersdal township just before 1am on Sunday (23:00 GMT on Saturday).
“It is reported that about 12 unknown suspects in a white kombi [a minibus] and a silver sedan opened fire at tavern patrons and continued to shoot randomly as they fled the scene,” the police said in a statement.
“The tavern is licensed,” it added.
Authorities said the wounded were taken to hospital.

Al Jazeera’s Ama Boateng reports.
Imraan Buccus is a political analyst focusing on socioeconomics in South Africa. 
He says the motive for the shooting isn't clear.
title: Manhunt under way after gunmen kill nine near South Africa’s Johannesburg

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Crypto mines have proliferated in Texas, drawn by cheap land, tax incentives, and a deregulated energy market. Their rapid expansion is causing significant conflict with local communities, particularly over noise pollution. Residents report constant, intolerable noise from cooling systems, leading to health complaints and plummeting property values.
Legal action is being taken against the operators, with lawsuits alleging the disturbances cause physical and mental harm. Attempts by communities to gain local control and enforce noise ordinances have so far been unsuccessful. The mines represent a clash between industrial growth, which brings investment and jobs, and the right of residents to peaceful enjoyment of their homes.

Al Jazeera’s Phil Lavelle reports from Granbury, Texas.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In Sudan, the RSF is expanding attacks into Kordofan after seizing control of Darfur.
The Sudan Doctors Network says at least 16 people were killed in Dilling, with civilians among the dead.
More than 100,000 people have been killed in the conflict, and over 14 million displaced.
Speaking to Al Jazeera, Mohammed Rifaat of the International Organization for Migration says women and children are fleeing alone, often separated from male relatives.
He says many have walked for more than eight days to reach White Nile State, facing harassment at militia checkpoints.
Rifaat warns families are arriving with no shelter, healthcare or belongings after months without assistance.
He says the escalating brutality and limited humanitarian access raise grave concerns for civilians still trapped in conflict areas.

China is facing a demographic crisis with fewer young people choosing to marry and have children. But the government may have found a solution – at least in the short term.

Al Jazeera’s Katrina Yu reports from Beijing, China.

She says there are multiple factors that contribute to China's demographic crisis.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Civil defence teams in Gaza have rescued five people, including a child and two women, trapped under a collapsed building.
The three-storey house in the Sheikh Radwan area, northwest of Gaza City, collapsed following weeks of heavy rain and flooding. 
Several buildings already damaged from Israeli air strikes over the past two years, have caved in due to extreme weather. 

Civil defence teams are also pressing ahead with efforts in other areas of Gaza to recover bodies of Palestinians buried under rubble.
Harsh winter weather has made recovery operations more difficult and increased the risk of buildings collapsing.
Body parts and bones are being collected for identification.
Thousands of bodies are believed to be buried under the remains of destroyed buildings.

Al Jazeera’s Tareq Abu Azzoum has more from Gaza City, Palestine.
